-- Israel Short-Term Bills Advance on Speculation Rates to Decline
-- B y   S h a r o n   W r o b e l
-- 2011-12-20T12:16:25Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-12-20/israel-short-term-bills-advance-on-speculation-rates-to-decline.html
Israel ’s short-term bonds rose on
speculation the Bank of Israel will lower  interest rates  in
coming months to bolster the economy as inflation slows.  The yield on the Makam bills due October 2012 dropped one
basis point, or 0.01 percentage point, to 2.53 percent at 2:04
p.m. in Tel Aviv. The yield has retreated 28 basis points since
the notes started trading last month. Shorter-term maturities
are more sensitive to rate fluctuations. The rate on the 5.5
percent notes due January 2022 rose from the lowest since Nov.
7, gaining one basis point to 4.56 percent.  Annual inflation slowed to 2.6 percent in November, the
slowest pace this year. Consumer prices may rise 2.2 percent in
the next 12 months compared with a forecast of 2.3 percent last
month, according to a survey of economists released by the  Bank
of Israel  yesterday. It lowered the benchmark interest rate to
2.75 percent in November and the next rate decision is scheduled
for Dec. 26.  “The yield on the Makam has fallen below the current
interest rate level, which shows that the market is pricing in
an interest-rate cut,” said Moshik Yaniv, head of the local
fixed-income desk at Migdal Capital Markets Ltd. in Tel Aviv.
“A slowdown in inflation and concern about  Europe ’s sovereign
debt crisis will keep yields in a downward direction as the
central bank is expected to lower borrowing costs in the coming
months to boost growth.”  Economic Outlook  One-year interest-rate swaps , an indicator of investor
expectations for rates in the next 12 months, rose from the
lowest since September 2010, gaining three basis points to 2.35
percent.  “Our fixed income outlook is anchored by our expectations
of a further 50 basis points of interest rate cuts by the Bank
of Israel in the next six months,” London-based  Daniel Hewitt ,
Barclays Capital’s senior emerging market economist, wrote in a
report to clients today. Barclays forecasts economic growth will
slow to 2.5 percent in 2012 after 4.8 percent this year.  The central bank is likely to cut its growth forecast for
next year to around 2.9 percent amid the European debt crisis,
Governor  Stanley Fischer  said on Dec. 7. The bank in September
forecast growth of 3.2 percent in 2012 after an expansion of 4.7
percent in 2011.  The yield on the CPI-linked bond due in June 2013 rose one
basis point to 0.70 percent. The two-year breakeven rate, the
difference between inflation-linked bonds and similar-maturity
fixed-rate government debt, climbed from the lowest since Nov.
15, increasing three basis points to 185, implying an average
annual inflation rate of 1.85 percent. The government’s target
range for inflation is 1 percent to 3 percent.  The shekel, down 6.8 percent this year, strengthened 0.5
percent to 3.7796 a dollar. The  Tel-Bond 40 index  of corporate
bonds dropped for a seventh day, declining 0.2 percent.  To contact the reporter on this story:
